{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"30127725-c30a-42ce-89cb-9c9d153ad471","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\nHere are the main tools for analyzing `.dmp` files from .NET apps:\n\n**1. `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform, easiest)\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\nUseful commands inside the REPL:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack\n- `pe` — print last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n- `threads` — list all threads\n\n**2. `lldb` with SOS** (Linux)\n```bash\ndotnet-sos install\nlldb --core your-file.dmp\n```\nThen: `clrstack`, `pe`, `dso`, etc.\n\n**3. WinDbg / Visual Studio** (Windows)\nOpen the `.dmp` file directly; load SOS with `.loadby sos coreclr`.\n\n---\n\n**Quick triage checklist:**\n1. Run `pe` to see if there's an unhandled exception with a stack trace.\n2. Run `threads` then `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` on the faulting thread.\n3. Check `dumpheap -stat` if you suspect an OOM.\n\nWould you like me to walk you through running any of these tools on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b075b587-0797-4543-9231-e628e27c71e1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo the skill is not appropriate here. I should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":458,"requestId":"A0D5:35214E:9AC48F:BDE07F:6A013827"},"id":"a83f9042-3088-46c0-a95b-e6cb70276924","timestamp":"2026-05-11T02:00:19.866Z","parentId":"072a7220-2b0f-4e99-95d1-a3fc969144e1"}
